rComments: He gave me the lowest grade I have ever received at U of T and to this day I do not understand why- very unclear and unfair grader. He attempted to cram too much information in his lectures and overall made the course difficult. I love the subject material but am disappointed at how this class turned out.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Tough grader', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Really pretentious. Lectures lack coherence. Made us watch three movies and read a book without mentioning them again. Irritating number of assignments. Had an analysis due two weeks before an essay. Unnecessary.

Professor Jennings was a perfectly nice professor, however I found his lectures to be dry at times and he attempted to cram too much into a two hour slot. Attempting to lecture on two different topics fully in less than two hours generally didn't work, especially because he (thankfully) gave us a break after 50 minutes.

Prof Jennings is super cute - let's just make that clear. He's also articulate, organized and motivating. He does an amazing job discussing colonialism all around the world, and teaches through a variety of mediums. His grading criteria is not very clear, but he values creativity and research.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lecture heavy', 'Amazing lectures']

rComments: Probably my favourite prof I had this year, lectures were always interesting and approached colonialism from pretty much every perspective. Felt crammed for time, especially when we covered decolonization. Course would be better off as a full year, rather than a half year. Also, he's a babe.

This was a required course and many are not history majors so some didn't enjoy it, but Jennings is truly passionate about WWII-era French history. He was engaging and brought in his own research, images, and primary sources, which was a nice touch.  I didn't have to read any of the texts or watch any films required but many struggled. Great prof!
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Participated in every class and was blindsided at the end with low participation marks with no explanation. Most of the mark was given at the end so there wasn't time for improvement.
Loves students who participate. Lecture style is very boring
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Possibly irrelevant but: nice person. Smiles a LOT. Like between sentences. Lectures articulately, sometimes funny, & can occasionally get very detailed (especially about his research interests). Likes technologylecture aids. Do the readings because you'll need context to actually gain from lecture. Would retake.

Jennings was awful. Completely unhelpful. Lectures were a waste, since he just ranted through most of them. I found myself having almost no notes after two hours of class. Would not recommend any course with him.

Professor Jennings was great and used a lot of interactive to illustrate his point (i.e. movies, objects from the time period etc.) However, the problem I had with this course is that he could not put France in the broader European context. I wish he had put his PowerPoints on the course website as some of the information/pictures were fascinating

Jennings is very intelligent, insightful and gets that history is not just a linear chain of events. His lectures are a reflection of this fact. Students would understand lectures a lot better if they just did the readings before each lecture. I found that many of my friends did not do so and were lost in class. Overall, interesting course.

Jennings seems like a very nice person, but is useless as a lecturer. Lectures are all over the place subject-wise. Talks an awful lot, but I never have any notes. Too much reading. He's a touch full of himself. A lot of French, not European history. Should be interesting material, but taught in a very disjointed manner.

He is good looking but not as hot as everyone says! His teaching is okay, he is very very organized and has good diction. Sometimes goes into too much detail on one topic, which while interesting is not as relevant for the exam. Overall I enjoyed his class.
Appears to be the biggest waste of space in the history department.  Seems like he spends every day trying to justify his job. Evidence of why we need less European historians in Canada.
Always has a sickly smile. If you are faking it, please stop.
yum!
He's very good looking, which doesn't make him a good lecturer but nice to look at. He seemed smart and funny, but he rushed over a lot of information toward the end of the semester.

He's a terrible prof. He favours ppl. who speak french. His lectures are all over the place. He keeps showing slides that bore everybody in class...and have nothing to do with course content. And, he gets obsessed with certain periods of history * goes on and on about that specific topic forever.
he's hot

He's okay, but his lectures really aren't that great, and he doesn't really convey what's important either for the general understand of the history itself or for the exam.  Best merit is appearance, but that only counts for so much.

I agree with that the magnitude of content in his lectures is too much to touch on in the given timeframe.  The original course only spanned WWI and WWII, but he extended it to cover from 1900 to the Balkans (90's) so some material is delivered hastely.
